msDesc.head: Hrabanus Maurus, Commentary on Maccabees, Ezra, Nehemiah and Judith

watermark.term: The letters PVH in a frame, above a shield surrounded by a garland and an unidentified motif.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. qui frater erat seleuci

p.note: Top left corner in blue ink, current signum.

Top of page, in black ink by a 19th century hand: Kgl. Bibl. 1734-års Kat. Theol. in 4o fol. no 4; centre page: Libri Machabaeorum, Eusdrae et Judith cum Explicatione Rabani Mauri; bottom left corner in brown ink: N. 4..

binding.p: Later, probably early modern, binding. Tawed leather over wooden boards. Spine, in brown ink: No 4. pars s lIbri; stamped in gold: A 138; brown ink on paper label: e. 30. 4.; underneath a partially torn paper label: 40.

history.provenance: Unknown origin and early provenance. The manuscript has been at the National Library since at least the 17th century. It is listed in Jaches's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as nr 149 in fol., and in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e) as nr 4 theol. in fol. The spine also carries the signum e. 30. 4. from Hammarsköld’s 19th century catalogue (U 133), as well as two unidentified signa (only partially legible).

msItem.note: Two leaves, and , have been placed in the wrong order. ends with Judith 16:2 and contains the end of the commentary on Judith. The explicit cited is found on .

The main portion of the commentary is written in a smaller script next to the main text and keyed to it by the use of lemmata. There is also a secondary layer in the margins consisiting of titles and references to authorities. This layer also seems to be part of the planned design.

supportDesc.condition: The parchment is of an uneven quality and somewhat worn; it has a tear on . There are also a few repairs, e.g. on . On and small rectangular pieces have been cut out, no loss of text. , smudge or dirt, text still legible.

layout.note: The text has an elborately designed layout with a main text and a commentary next to it. The written area of the main text expands or retracts in size dependig on the amount of commentary. At its largest it extends over 27 lines and all of the text surface, e.g. . In other cases the commentary may take up the majority of the page, e.g. . The commentary is written in half the size of the main text and is keyed to it with the help of lemmata. The ruling is a complex grid structure that takes into account the commentary. The ruling is made in lead or faint ink. Prickings in the margins.

p.note: Extensive marginal and interlinear glossing througout. The majority of the glosses seem to be by the scribe (or a contemporary hand) and are probably part of the planned commentary. These glosses consist of references to authorities, corrections and occasional additions. There is also a layer of extensive, but almost invisible, glossing in lead or silver point, e.g. and . In addition, there are scattered additions by a later medieval hand, e.g. and more frequently on .
Titles and notes in ink by an early modern hand.

decoDesc.p: Main text in brown ink. Capitals in blue or red.
